            margin-top: 20px;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>ExpenseHub Demo Guide</h1>
    
    <p>This guide will help you demonstrate the ExpenseHub application to faculty using two different user accounts simultaneously.</p>
    
    <h2>Why You Need Different Browser Contexts</h2>
    <p>Web browsers share cookies across tabs and windows by default. This means if you log in as User 1 in one tab and User 2 in another tab, the second login will overwrite the first, causing User 1 to be logged out.</p>
    
    <h2>Methods to Demonstrate Multiple Users</h2>
    
    <div class="method">
        <h3>Method 1: Different Browsers (Recommended)</h3>
        <div class="step">
            <span class="step-number">1</span>
            Open Chrome and login as User 1
        </div>
        <div class="step">
            <span class="step-number">2</span>
            Open Firefox (or Edge) and login as User 2
        </div>
        <div class="step">
            <span class="step-number">3</span>
            Place the windows side by side for a clear demonstration
        </div>
    </div>
    
    <div class="method">
        <h3>Method 2: Incognito/Private Window</h3>
        <div class="step">
            <span class="step-number">1</span>
            Open a regular browser window and login as User 1
        </div>
        <div class="step">
            <span class="step-number">2</span>
            Open an incognito/private window (Ctrl+Shift+N in Chrome) and login as User 2
        </div>
        <div class="step">
            <span class="step-number">3</span>
            Arrange both windows side by side
        </div>
    </div>
    
    <div class="method">
        <h3>Method 3: Chrome Profiles</h3>
        <div class="step">
            <span class="step-number">1</span>
            In Chrome, click on your profile icon in the top-right corner
        </div>
        <div class="step">
            <span class="step-number">2</span>
            Choose "Add" to create a new profile
        </div>
        <div class="step">
            <span class="step-number">3</span>
            Login as User 1 in one profile and User 2 in the other profile
        </div>
    </div>
    
    <h2>Demonstrating Group Sharing</h2>
    
    <div class="step">
        <span class="step-number">1</span>
        In the User 1 window, create a new group by clicking "Create Group"
    </div>
    <div class="step">
        <span class="step-number">2</span>
        Once created, find the group under "Your Groups" and copy the Group ID using the copy icon (ðŸ“‹)
    </div>
    <div class="step">
        <span class="step-number">3</span>
        In the User 2 window, click "Join Group" and paste the Group ID
    </div>
    <div class="step">
        <span class="step-number">4</span>
        Show how User 2 is now a member of the group created by User 1
    </div>
    <div class="step">
        <span class="step-number">5</span>
        Create a group expense in either account and demonstrate how it appears for both users
    </div>
    
    <div class="note">
        <strong>Note:</strong> If you encounter any session issues, try clearing your browser cookies or using one of the other methods described above.
    </div>
    
    <a href="/dashboard" class="btn">Return to Dashboard</a>
</body>
</html>